Package cetus.hir

Class Identifier

  • java.lang.Object
    • cetus.hir.Expression
      • cetus.hir.IDExpression
        • cetus.hir.Identifier
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Printable, Traversable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Comparable<Expression>
    public class Identifier
extends IDExpression
    Identifier represents a valid C identifier which has a matching variable declarator. It is important to notice that construction of a new Identifier object with an arbitrary string is not recommended at all because of possible inconsistency. For this reason such constructors are protected. For pass writers accustomed to such usage may still be able to create a string identifier through SymbolTools.getOrphanID(String). However, the correctness of any analysis/transformation after introducing such "orphan" identifier is not guaranteed.

      • Identifier

        protected Identifier​(java.lang.String name)
        Returns a new incomplete identifier with the given string name. It is incomplete in that it does not have access to its relevant variable declaration/declarator. This constructor is used only internally. Pass writers are strongly recommended to construct an identifier out of the relevant symbol object.
        Parameters:
        name - the raw string name.

      • hashCode

        protected int hashCode​(int h)
        Description copied from class: Expression
        Returns cumulative hash code with the given initial value, h. This is intended for optimizing memory usage when computing hash code of an expression object. Previous approach constructs a string representation of the expression to get the hash code while this approach uses the same algorithm as String.hashCode() without creating a string. All sub classes of Expression have there specific implementations of this method and Expression.hashCode() simply returns hashCode(0).
        Overrides:
        hashCode in class Expression
